&gt; The equation you would have needed to use to calculate how
&gt; fast the objects are traveling is Ep + Ek = Ep + Ek (Ek=kinetic
&gt; energy, and Ep=potential energy).
&gt; Ek on the left side would cancel, because v=0 (v=velocity). The
&gt; Ep on the right side would also cancel out, since h=0 (h=height).
&gt; That leaves Ep=Ek. Ep=mgh, and Ek=0.5mv^2. (the &quot; ^ &quot; sign
&gt; represents &quot;to the power of&quot;).
&gt; Then you&#39;d have mgh=0.5mv^2. Mass cancels, making leaving
&gt; us with gh=0.5v^2.
&gt; Thus, I conclude that mass doesn&#39;t affect how fast you fall, only
&gt; how high you are at the start.
&gt;
&gt; PS: weight is a force, in newtons. Mass is usually in kilograms, or
&gt; pounds etc.
